## Conversation
User asked "Is our PaginatedIterator implementation any good? Can we do better?"
I reviewed weave/utils/paginated_iterator.py and flagged: (1) @lru_cache on a
method = process-lifetime memory leak (B019, suppressed via noqa); (2) a
stateful __next__ vs restartable __iter__ inconsistency; (3) a latent
offset+limit bug in _get_one; plus minor nits. User said "ok do that as a
stack of PRs", scoping to what I'd offered: "per-instance cache + drop the
broken offset path". This commit is PR1 of that stack (the cache fix). The
iteration-model change was explicitly NOT in scope (it contradicts a
deliberate prior commit #6115 and touches restartability semantics).

## Actions
- Read paginated_iterator.py, its tests, and the call.py construction site.
- git log on the file; confirmed B019 noqa is long-standing.
- Replaced the @lru_cache-decorated _fetch_page with a bounded per-instance
  OrderedDict LRU (DEFAULT_MAX_CACHED_PAGES=128, matching the old implicit
  lru_cache default bound). move_to_end on hit; popitem(last=False) to evict.
- Added two tests: page reuse within an instance (fetch-count at the
  fetch_func boundary), and weakref-based release-after-del (the actual leak
  regression).
- ruff --fix: clean. pytest tests/utils/test_paginated_iterator.py: 5 passed.

