## Dead Ends
- Considered a plain unbounded per-instance dict: simpler, but would regress
  peak memory for large forward iterations (old code bounded to ~128 pages).
  Chose bounded OrderedDict LRU to preserve that bound.
- Considered per-instance functools.lru_cache built in __init__: 2 lines but
  creates a self-reference cycle (self -> cache -> bound method -> self),
  GC-collectable but icky and not refcount-immediate. Rejected for the
  explicit OrderedDict (no cycle, debuggable).

## Hints for Future Agents
- The 128 bound is a const at top; it is NOT a constructor param on purpose
  (no caller needs to tune it; avoid speculative config).
- Caching is an optimization, not correctness: restartable iteration and
  random access work without it (they just refetch). Tests must not assert on
  internal cache structure -- the release test uses weakref (observable),
  the reuse test counts fetch_func calls (the external seam).
- Worktree gotcha: master lives in another worktree; use
  `gt create --onto master`, never `gt checkout master`, in this workspace.

## Codebase Discoveries
